  "solution": "The high-performing department likely excels at operational efficiency and patient experience quality, not resource quantity. When winter volume spikes 40%, satisfaction drops because: (1) Communication breaks down — patients don't know what's happening or why they're waiting, (2) Staff become stretched and stressed, reducing presence/attentiveness, (3) Throughput slows, creating bottlenecks. The real drivers of satisfaction are: speed-through-system, staff engagement/morale, clarity and communication, and perception of being valued/cared-for — NOT bed count. The solution isn't 'add beds' but: (1) improve operational efficiency to move patients faster, (2) invest in communication protocols to keep patients informed, (3) protect staff resilience during surges (staffing ratios, breaks, support), (4) design workflows that preserve staff presence with patients. This explains why the best department has fewer beds — they waste no bed, move patients quickly, and staff stay engaged. Adding beds to a poorly-communicated, staff-stressed system adds congestion without fixing satisfaction."
